ng role in the Soviet computer industry, including their success in convincing Nikita Khrushchev to build a secret Silicon Valley.The book is rich with details of Barr’s and Sarant’s intriguing andexciting personal lives, their families, as well as their integration into Russian society. Engineering Communism follows the two spies through Sarant’s death and Barr’s unbelievable return to the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommunistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aElectrical engineerszSoviet UnionvBiography. 0aEspionage, SovietzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSpieszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030010874340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030012795940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300127959423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300127959/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY